          "body": "Deuteronomy 18:15-19 is one of the Old Testament's most theologically loaded passages. Moses announces that Yahweh will raise up a Prophet 'like me' from among the Israelites (18:15). The comparison to Moses is carefully chosen. In Deuteronomy's own assessment, no prophet arose like Moses — who knew God face to face (34:10) — until Jesus of Nazareth. The text does not say 'a succession of prophets' first; the grammar of 18:15 is singular ('a prophet'), pointing to an individual. Israel's post-Mosaic prophetic tradition (Elijah, Isaiah, Jeremiah) partially fulfills the type but never fully satisfies it — their contemporaries recognized this (John 1:21; 7:40-41). Three features mark the coming Prophet as categorically greater than all others: (1) Yahweh will put His words in his mouth — not inspire him from a distance but direct speech-endowment; (2) he will speak everything God commands, nothing less, nothing more (18:18); (3) refusing to hear him triggers direct divine accountability (18:19). The New Testament applies this text explicitly to Jesus (Acts 3:22-26; 7:37) and Jesus appropriates the vocabulary Himself (John 12:49; 14:10). He is the Prophet who does not merely transmit God's words — He IS the Word made flesh (John 1:14)."
