          "title": "The test of true prophecy — a canon of discernment",
          "body": "The chapter closes with a question from the congregation's own heart: 'How will we know the word which the Lord has not spoken?' (18:21). Moses does not dismiss the question. He provides a concrete, non-mystical criterion: predictive accuracy. If a prophet speaks in Yahweh's name and the word does not come true, that prophet spoke presumptuously — do not fear him (18:22). The negative criterion ('does not come true') is the diagnostic test. It is worth noting what Moses does not say. He does not say: trust charisma, trust sincerity, trust cultural influence, trust ecstatic experience. He says: wait for the word to meet reality. This test has limits — it addresses the false prophet's exposure after the fact — and Deuteronomy 13 supplies the complementary positive test (doctrinal fidelity, not signs alone). Together, the two chapters provide the Mosaic canon of prophetic discernment. Peter Davids and Douglas Moo both note that the false-prophet warning is the necessary complement to the Prophet-promise: the greater the authority attributed to the Prophet, the greater the danger of counterfeits. Chapter 18 ends not with triumphalism but with sober-eyed discernment as a covenant obligation."
