        "excerpt": "The Lord is their inheritance, as He promised them. — 18:2",
        "body": "The opening pericope establishes a theological principle before it issues any instruction: Yahweh does not merely provide for the Levites — He IS their provision. The statement 'the Lord is their inheritance' (18:2) is one of the most compressed theological claims in Deuteronomy, packing into five Hebrew words (yahweh hu nachalato) what the Psalter will later develop across dozens of poems (Pss 16:5; 73:25-26; 142:5). The Levites stand in a unique economic vulnerability — no land, no agricultural base, no capital — and that vulnerability is the form their spiritual privilege takes. Closeness to God entails dispossession of everything else.\n\nThe community's obligation to support the priests (vv. 3-4) is grounded explicitly in divine election: 'the Lord your God has chosen him and his sons from all your tribes to stand and serve in the name of the Lord forever' (18:5). The obligation is not humanitarian — it is covenantal. You give the shoulder, the cheeks, the stomach, the firstfruits, the first shearing because God chose this tribe. The tithe is not charity; it is covenant maintenance.\n\nThe provision for the itinerant Levite (vv. 6-8) extends the principle to its most practical edge. A Levite living in any provincial town retains the right to travel to the central sanctuary and serve with full equality — 'equal portions' (18:8). The central sanctuary does not become an elite guild. Entry is by divine election, not seniority or geography. This egalitarianism within the priestly order anticipates the New Testament's radically leveled priesthood of all believers, in which the High Priest has opened the way for every believer to draw near (Heb 10:19-22; 1 Pet 2:9).\n\nChuck Swindoll notes that the Levites' arrangement is 'God's deliberate design to keep the servants of the Word from the distracting entanglements of property management.' The landlessness is grace, not deprivation. The God who is their portion is inexhaustible in a way that no allotment of Canaanite soil ever could be.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nachalah* (inheritance) appears five times across vv. 1-2 and 8, creating a sustained meditation on what Levi inherits. *Cheleq* (portion, share) is used in v. 8 for the Levites' equal share at the sanctuary. *Sharat* (minister, serve in a cultic capacity) and *amad* (stand before) are the two verbs of priestly vocation — standing in the presence and ministering in the service."
