        "body": "Moses now delivers the Promise that the occult prohibition made necessary. The nations get their hidden knowledge through divination; Israel will get hers through a Prophet whom Yahweh personally raises up, authorizes, and directs. The Promise is delivered first in Moses's own voice (18:15) and then repeated verbatim in the direct speech of God (18:18) — the double-announcement underscores the Promise's divine solemnity.\n\nThree features of the Promise demand careful interpretation. First, the Prophet is 'like me' (18:15, 18). The comparison is to Moses as the founding covenant mediator: the one who stood between God and the people at Sinai (Deut 5:5), who received the law directly from Yahweh (Exod 33:11), who spoke 'face to face' with God in a way no other prophet did (Deut 34:10). The likeness is not generic — it is typological. Every subsequent Israelite prophet partially resembles Moses; none fully satisfies the comparison. Joshua leads but does not legislate. Elijah confronts but does not mediate the covenant. Isaiah, Jeremiah, and Ezekiel speak magnificently but always defer to the Mosaic law. The Qumran community expected a specific eschatological Prophet-like-Moses (1QS 9:11), and the crowds of Jesus's day recognized the category (John 6:14; 7:40). The New Testament's application is explicit: Acts 3:22-26 (Peter's Pentecost sermon) and Acts 7:37 (Stephen's speech) both identify Jesus as the fulfillment. Jesus Himself uses the same theological vocabulary — 'the Father who sent Me has Himself given Me a commandment about what to say and what to speak' (John 12:49; cf. 14:10, 24) — a direct echo of 18:18.\n\nSecond, 'I will put My words in his mouth' (18:18). The image is not inspiration-from-a-distance but direct speech-endowment. The same idiom is used of Jeremiah's prophetic commission (Jer 1:9) and of the angel's instruction to Balaam (Num 22:38). But applied to the coming Prophet, the force exceeds all these: the words are not relayed through the prophet's fallible cognition but placed in his mouth by the one whose words are the architecture of reality. John 1:14 and 17:8 are the New Testament's expansion of this claim: Jesus does not merely transmit the Father's words — He speaks what He has heard from the Father, because He and the Father are one.\n\nThird, the hearing of the Prophet is commanded: 'you shall listen to him' (18:15); 'whoever will not listen to My words which he shall speak in My name, I Myself will require it of him' (18:19). The Promise carries an obligation of total attention. The Transfiguration echoes this exactly — the Father's voice from the cloud says 'This is My beloved Son, with whom I am well-pleased; listen to Him' (Matt 17:5), the New Testament's quotation of Deuteronomy 18:15. The Prophet's word is not optional counsel; it is authoritative divine speech, and refusing it triggers divine accountability.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Navi* (prophet) — a spokesperson, mouthpiece. *Qerev* (from among) — literally 'from the midst of,' emphasizing the Prophet's genuine humanity: he comes from within the covenant people, not from outside. *Davar* (word) dominates vv. 18-22 — the entire question of the true Prophet turns on whose davar is in his mouth. *Shem* (name) in vv. 19-22 carries the full weight of divine authority — to speak in the name of Yahweh is to bear His commission; to abuse that name is capital treason."
