        "title": "The false prophet and the test of true prophecy",
        "range": "18:20-22",
        "excerpt": "When a prophet speaks in the name of the Lord, if the thing does not come about or come true, that is the thing which the Lord has not spoken. — 18:22",
        "body": "The Promise of the true Prophet immediately generates the problem of false prophets. If Israel is commanded to hear the Prophet Yahweh raises up, the danger of counterfeit voices claiming that authorization is acute. Moses addresses the problem with characteristic Deuteronomic precision: two types of false prophecy and one public test.\n\nVerse 20 identifies two distinct forms of false prophecy. The first speaks presumptuously in Yahweh's name — claiming divine authorization for words God has not given. This is the zadon-prophet: driven by insolent self-assertion, he invents divine speech. The second speaks in the name of other gods — explicitly serving foreign deities while using prophetic language. Both receive the same verdict: death. The punishment is severe because the crime is cosmically serious: to fraudulently claim Yahweh's authorization is to misrepresent the character and word of the God who is making covenant with Israel. Deuteronomy 13:1-5 complements this passage with the opposite scenario — a prophet whose prediction comes true but who leads Israel toward other gods — establishing that predictive accuracy alone is insufficient, and doctrinal fidelity must be the first filter.\n\nThe congregation's question in v. 21 is both natural and honest: 'How will we know?' Moses's answer is pragmatic and non-mystical: wait for the word to meet reality. If a prophet claims to speak in Yahweh's name and the thing does not happen, that prophet has spoken presumptuously — 'you shall not be afraid of him' (18:22). The combination of 'do not be afraid' with the false-prophet verdict is suggestive: some false prophets wielded psychological power through fear, through claims of divine wrath if ignored. Moses deflates that power entirely. A word that does not come true has no claim on Israel's obedience or fear.\n\nJohn Calvin notes that this test does not prove the positive case — that a word's fulfillment guarantees divine origin — but it definitively exposes the negative: unfulfillment proves false prophecy. The positive guarantee requires the additional test of Deuteronomy 13 (conformity to revealed truth about Yahweh). Together, the two chapters give Israel a two-sided canon of discernment: content and fulfillment. Faithful preaching today operates on the same logic — the messenger who claims divine authority must be tested against the closed canon of Scripture, which is both the ultimate fulfillment of the Mosaic prophetic word and the standard against which every subsequent claim to divine speech must be measured.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Zadon* (presumptuousness, v.22) — pride-driven rebellion, insolent self-assertion; related to *zed* (arrogant, proud man) and *zud* (to act presumptuously, v.20). The false prophet's crime is not merely error but willful self-exaltation. *Gur* (be afraid of, v.22) — to dread, to stand in fear before; Moses uses the exact same verb used for Israel's terror at the divine fire in v.16 (*I will die*). Do not give the false prophet the fear that belongs to the living God alone."
